        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-11 20:13:55.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\n(6 comments)\n\nSome of the javascript library files and css files are the same across the monitoring, deployment, and the editor client. I'm not an expert on Javascript but is there a way of placing those files in a common place so all clients can use them?",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
      {
        "id": "7b2beaf16ee7be467149aa61b0fdd284e71d1067",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 57,
          "name": "Pamela Dragosh",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "pd1248@att.com",
          "username": "pdragosh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-12 12:19:46.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nLiam, organization of javascript is yet another TODO item that we will need to address by Dublin. My thinking is that we organize javascript code such that they are in libraries, with adequate JUnit tests (TBD that process). With them being in libraries (TBD that format), then they would be accessible from multiple GUIs. eg. The future Policy Designer located in SDC, the current Policy Portal GUI, and perhaps in localized run-time instances of PDP engines. To start, perhaps Apex could be the place to prototype such work .",
        "patchset_number": 2
      },
